  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap stack">
 
      <div class="card">
        <span class="eyebrow">Artifact Story</span>
        <h2 class="h2">Situation</h2>
        <div class="stack">
          <p>As a product and its documentation grow, different teams may begin using different words for the same concept. Writers may also encounter internal shorthand, outdated interface labels, customer language, and similar terms that represent different product objects.</p>
          <p>Without a governed reference, those differences can create inconsistencies across help articles, interface content, release notes, support materials, training, search results, and AI generated answers. New writers may also have difficulty determining which term is preferred or who can validate its meaning.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
 
      <div class="card">
        <span class="eyebrow">Artifact Story</span>
        <h2 class="h2">Task</h2>
        <div class="stack">
          <p>I needed to design a terminology resource that helped writers understand the product vocabulary without contradicting existing guides or introducing definitions based only on individual memory.</p>
          <p>The system needed to identify preferred terms, explain distinctions between related concepts, preserve established interface language, and clarify which teams were responsible for validating terminology decisions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
 
      <div class="card">
        <span class="eyebrow">Artifact Story</span>
        <h2 class="h2">Action</h2>
        <div class="stack">
          <p>I reviewed existing ScoopRoute guides and style guidance before drafting each entry so established documentation remained the source of truth.</p>
          <p>I structured the term bank around concise entries that define the preferred term, explain how it should be used, and distinguish it from related or potentially conflicting language. Examples include the difference between a customer and a service location, a route and a scheduled stop, and a recurring delivery service and an individual visit.</p>
          <p>I also incorporated cross team ownership into the glossary. Documentation manages terminology consistency and approves changes, while Product, Design, Support, Billing, Operations, and other subject matter experts validate the meaning of terms within their product areas.</p>
          <p>When remembered terminology conflicted with existing guides, I preserved the published term as preferred and treated the alternate wording as context, a search synonym, or a candidate for further review.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
 
      <div class="card">
        <span class="eyebrow">Artifact Story</span>
        <h2 class="h2">Result</h2>
        <div class="stack">
          <p>The term bank creates a shared vocabulary for writers and partner teams. It helps new contributors understand product concepts faster, reduces conflicting language across content, improves alignment between documentation and the interface, and makes terminology decisions easier to review and maintain.</p>
          <p>The system also strengthens search and AI readiness by connecting preferred terms with alternate language without allowing those alternatives to replace approved product terminology.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
 
    </div>
